  "prompt": "What should be my individual subject scores in NEET 2017?",
  "response": "To give you specific, personalized advice on what your individual subject scores *should* be for NEET 2017, I need to clarify that the NEET 2017 exam has already been conducted, and the results are out.\n\nHowever, I can still give you helpful information based on past NEET cutoff scores and trends, which will help you plan future NEET attempts.\n\n**To give you the best advice, tell me:**\n\n*   **What is your category?** (General, OBC, SC, ST, EWS, etc.)\n*   **What is your target medical college, state or rank?** (If you have one in mind)\n*   **Are you planning for NEET 2024?**\n\n**Here's some general information about NEET subject-wise score distribution that is typically observed, which will help in planning:**\n\n*   **Total Marks:** 720 (180 questions x 4 marks each)\n*   **Physics:** 180 marks (45 questions)\n*   **Chemistry:** 180 marks (45 questions)\n*   **Biology (Botany & Zoology):** 360 marks (90 questions)\n\n**General Strategies for Scoring Well (Irrespective of the Year):**\n\n*   **Biology is Key:** Biology has the highest weightage (360 marks). Aim for a very strong score in this section. Many successful students score above 300/360 in Biology.\n*   **Equal Importance to Physics and Chemistry:** While Biology is crucial, don't neglect Physics and Chemistry. A balanced approach is vital.\n*   **Accuracy Over Attempts:** Negative marking exists (-1 for each wrong answer). Focus on accuracy. Attempt only those questions you are reasonably sure about.\n*   **NCERT Focus:** NCERT textbooks are the foundation. Master the concepts in NCERT thoroughly.\n*   **Mock Tests and Past Papers:** Solve plenty of mock tests and previous years' NEET question papers to get familiar with the exam pattern, time management, and difficulty level.\n*   **Time Management:** Practice time management during mock tests. Allocate time for each section.\n*   **Regular Revision:** Regular revision is essential to retain concepts.\n\n**Past NEET Cutoff Trends (General Idea - will vary each year):**\n\n*   **General Category:** To get a good government medical college, aim for a score above 600. A score in the range of 620-650+ significantly improves your chances.\n*   **OBC/SC/ST:** Cutoffs are lower than the general category. Refer to official NEET cutoff data for previous years for specific category-wise cutoffs.\n\n**How to Determine Your Target Score:**\n\n1.  **Research Cutoffs:**  Look up the NEET cutoffs for your category and desired colleges for the past few years. This will give you a range to aim for.\n2.  **Add a Buffer:**  Add a buffer of at least 20-30 marks to the previous year's cutoff to account for increasing competition and potential changes in exam difficulty.\n\n**Example Scenario:**\n\nLet's say you are in the General category and want to get into a decent government medical college in your state.  You find that the cutoff for those colleges last year was around 610.\n\n*   **Target Score:**  610 + 30 = 640\n\n**Therefore, you should be aiming for a total score of 640 or higher.**  This means you'll need to strategize your subject-wise preparation accordingly. This may translate to attempting almost the entire biology paper, having very high accuracy and then strategically selecting questions in physics and chemistry.\n\n**Once you provide me with the details of your category, your target college (or state), and the NEET year you are planning for, I can give you more tailored advice.**\n",
